1. e4 e5 { My choice for the Open Games is the Four Knights Scotch variation. } 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} { Developing the knight with tempi, hitting the e5-pawn, is our best move against the Open Games. } d6 { The Philidor Defence is a rare bird at our level but just in case it appears on the board here is our solution. } 
3. d4! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gd4e5]} { Opening the game and threatening to capture a pawn. } ( { There is no need for } 3.Nc3 { because our e-pawn is not attacked. } ) Bg4 { Much worse. } 
4. dxe5! Bxf3 ( 4...dxe5? 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Nxe5 { is winning for White. } ) 
5. Qxf3 dxe5 
6. Bc4! {[%cal Gf3b3][%csl Rf7]} { Hitting the weak f7-pawn and also planning Qb3 with a double attack. For more information on this exact line, and the chance to enjoy one of the best games ever, I would refer to the famous "Opera Game" between Paul Morphy and both Count Isouard and the Duke of Brunswick. } *

