3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is the starting position of the Scotch Four Knights Variation Opening. It's an excellent option for beginners, intermediate players and club experts. Our development is clear-cut: knights before bishops without breaking any basic opening rules. } { We can also reach this position via the direct Scotch Opening: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 but then our opponent has other decent options on their fourth move to sidestep our setup. } Bb4!? {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Rc3]} { Is worse. } 
5. Nxe5! { This line does have some tactical complications, but it will lead to positions in which only we can win the game. }Nxe5? ( { Black's best move is } 5...Qe7 { (against which we shall play } 6.Qd3 { returning the pawn for development) but at amateur level hardly anyone will find this move. } { You will mostly face the much weaker moves 5...Nxe5? or 5...Nxe4?! when our opponent is trying to get his pawn back but will end up in deep trouble. }) { Is the most played move between amateur players. } 
6. dxe5 Nxe4 
7. Qg4! {[%csl Rb4,Re4,Rg7]} Bxc3+ ( { If } 7...Nxc3 8.Qxb4 Nd5 9.Qg4 { with the idea } 9...O-O? 10.Bh6 { winning material. } ) 
8. bxc3 Nxc3? 
9. Qxg7 Rf8 
10. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8]} { Is already game over. } *

