1. e4 e5 { My choice for the Open Games is the Four Knights Scotch variation. } 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} { Developing the knight with tempi, hitting the e5-pawn, is our best move against the Open Games. } Nc6 { This is their most popular choice at all levels. Every now and then we might face a different defence of the pawn. Let's check them briefly. } 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. d4 { This is the starting position of the Scotch Four Knights Variation Opening. It's an excellent option for beginners, intermediate players and club experts. Our development is clear-cut: knights before bishops without breaking any basic opening rules. } { We can also reach this position via the direct Scotch Opening: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 but then our opponent has other decent options on their fourth move to sidestep our setup. } exd4 { Black's most popular move, which we will face most of the time. } 
5. Nxd4 { By eliminating the pawn on e5, we have more control over the center. If and when our opponent plays ...d6, he will have to play a passive game with his dark-squared bishop boxed in. Therefore, developing the bishop to c5 and, above all, to b4 is Black's main move in this position at all levels. } ( { The so-called 'Belgrade' gambit } 5.Nd5!? { is an interesting surprise weapon option for blitz and rapid, but not totally sound for classical play. } ) Bb4 {[%cal Yf6e4][%csl Rc3]} { Active play and fast development offset our opponent's lack of space. The bishop pins our knight on c3, and therefore they threaten to play ...Nxe4, winning a pawn. Playing ...d6 and developing the bishop on e7 is just asking for a cramped game. } 
6. Nxc6 ( { We are forced to exchange knights as } 6.Bd3? { would drop a piece. However, in doing so, we double one of their pawns and free the d-file. } ) bxc6 ( { Black can throw in } 6...Bxc3+? { at any given moment. We shouldn't worry too much about it as long as we don't lose material: our c1-bishop will cause havoc on the dark squares. } ) 
7. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 { However, is perfectly playable and quite popular as well so we should check it out. My proposal is: } 
8. exd5 cxd5 { If they castle, we also castle - no need to capture sacrificed pawns, handing over the initiative to them. } 
9. O-O { Transposing back to the main line. } ( { Even so, } 9.Qe2+ { might be a way to confuse them and take them (but also us!) out of the theory book. } ) *

