1. e4 e5 { My choice for the Open Games is the Four Knights Scotch variation. } 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} { Developing the knight with tempi, hitting the e5-pawn, is our best move against the Open Games. } Nc6 { This is their most popular choice at all levels. Every now and then we might face a different defence of the pawn. Let's check them briefly. } 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. d4 { This is the starting position of the Scotch Four Knights Variation Opening. It's an excellent option for beginners, intermediate players and club experts. Our development is clear-cut: knights before bishops without breaking any basic opening rules. } { We can also reach this position via the direct Scotch Opening: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 but then our opponent has other decent options on their fourth move to sidestep our setup. } exd4 { Black's most popular move, which we will face most of the time. } 
5. Nxd4 { By eliminating the pawn on e5, we have more control over the center. If and when our opponent plays ...d6, he will have to play a passive game with his dark-squared bishop boxed in. Therefore, developing the bishop to c5 and, above all, to b4 is Black's main move in this position at all levels. } ( { The so-called 'Belgrade' gambit } 5.Nd5!? { is an interesting surprise weapon option for blitz and rapid, but not totally sound for classical play. } ) Bb4 {[%cal Yf6e4][%csl Rc3]} { Active play and fast development offset our opponent's lack of space. The bishop pins our knight on c3, and therefore they threaten to play ...Nxe4, winning a pawn. Playing ...d6 and developing the bishop on e7 is just asking for a cramped game. } 
6. Nxc6 ( { We are forced to exchange knights as } 6.Bd3? { would drop a piece. However, in doing so, we double one of their pawns and free the d-file. } ) bxc6 ( { Black can throw in } 6...Bxc3+? { at any given moment. We shouldn't worry too much about it as long as we don't lose material: our c1-bishop will cause havoc on the dark squares. } ) 
7. Bd3 O-O { The most principal move, putting the king into safety before advancing in the center. } ( { If } 7...Bxc3+ 8.bxc3 { . } ) 
8. O-O d5 { Black needs to play this move as soon as possible in order to fight for the center, grab some space, develop his light-squared bishop and, hopefully, improve his pawn structure. } 
9. exd5 cxd5 { The key opening position. White has a superior pawn structure and clear development for the rest of his pieces. Black has also nearly finished their development, so we can consider the position to be roughly equal. } 
10. h3! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Although the most theoretical move in this position is } 10.Bg5 { , we will choose instead Kramnik's suggestion 10. h3, preventing our opponent from playing ...Bg4, and therefore securing the f3-square for our queen. } ) c6 
11. Qf3 Re8 ( { They can also try } 11...Bd6 { check out the very recently played model game between GM's Alsina Leal and Narciso Dublan [/variation/41248794/#/11/b] for the middlegame ideas in this line. } ) 
12. Bf4 { A great square for the bishop, controlling b8. } Bd6 
13. Rfe1 { The open file must be contested. } Be6 
14. Ne2 { Relocating the knight to a better position (d4, f4 or g3). } Rb8 
15. b3 c5 
16. Rad1 { With an interesting middlegame ahead. Our pawn structure is slightly better, both sides have safe kings and healthy development: anything can happen! More analysis and ideas can be found in the attached model game between former World Champion Vladimir Kramnik and top contender Levon Aronian [/variation/41248795/#/12/w]. } *

[Event "1.e4: A Positional Repertoire for Club Players"]
[White "1.2) 1.e4 e5 - Model Games"]
[Black "Kramnik, Vladimir vs. Aronian, Levon"]
[Date "2024.10.07"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C47"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41248795"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} Nc6 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. d4 exd4 
5. Nxd4 Bb4 
6. Nxc6 bxc6 
7. Bd3 O-O 
8. O-O d5 
9. exd5 cxd5 
10. h3 Re8 
11. Qf3 c6 
12. Bf4 { With his new idea 10. h3, Kramnik opt to develop his bishop to the f4 square, instead of pinning the knight on f6. Note that the bishop controls a very nice diagonal and also prevents them from playing ...Rb8. } Bd7!? { An unusual move. The bishop is usually developed to e6, but Aronian did not want to block the e-file. Other options are: } ( 12...Be6 13.Ne2 Bd6 14.Rfe1 c5 15.Rad1 15...Qb6 { But not 15...c4? 16.Bxc4! dxc4 17.Bxd6 winning material. } 16.Bxd6 Qxd6 17.Nf4 Rab8 18.b3 { and White has the initiative in the center, as in the game between Muzychuk and Zhao from the 2012 Istanbul Olympiad. Note the pressure that the black queen has to face along the d-file against the white rook. } ) ( 12...Bd6 13.Rfe1 Rxe1+ 14.Rxe1 Be6 $146 15.Ne2 15...c5 16.b3 { Preventing their pawns from advancing } 16...Rb8 17.Bxd6 Qxd6 18.Nf4 { as in the game between GM's Hovhannisyan and Zhigalko from a tournament in Jerusalem 2015. Again, White has the initiative in the center and can pressure along the e-file. } ) 
13. a3 Bxc3?! { As we have mentioned before, slightly damaging our pawn structure is not so important, whereas the bishop pair and control over the dark squares can be paramount. } 
14. bxc3 Ne4 
15. Rfe1 Qf6 ( { Aronian should have picked up the gauntlet here and captured the pawn with } 15...Nxc3 { . Kramnik does have compensation for the pawn, but probably not much more. } ) 
16. Bxe4 dxe4 
17. Qe3! Be6 
18. Rad1 { Black's position of difficult to hold. With opposite coloured bishops on the board, the initiative is key, and there are many weak dark squares. } Qf5 
19. Rd4 f6 
20. Rb1! ( { Of course, White must avoid } 20.Rxe4?! Bf7 { and Black bails out into a pure bishop and queen ending which will be a draw even a pawn down. } ) Bd5 
21. c4 Bf7 
22. Rb7 { And White should have followed up with Bd6 and c5 with total domination. In the end, the game finished in a draw after excellent defense by Aronian. } 1/2-1/2

