{ This grandmaster game was disputed very recently in the Catalonian Championship. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} Nc6 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. d4 exd4 
5. Nxd4 Bb4 
6. Nxc6 bxc6 
7. Bd3 d5 
8. exd5 cxd5 
9. O-O O-O 
10. h3 c6 
11. Qf3 Bd6 ( { Instead of } 11...Re8 { , Narciso Dublan prefers to relocate his dark-squared bishop. } ) 
12. Re1 { Occupying the e-file. } h6 { Preventing the pin on g5. } 
13. b3!? { Anticipating 13...Rb8 hitting the b2-pawn and maybe preparing Bb2 and/or Na4 ideas. } ( { Of course } 13.Bf4 { is a perfectly good move. } ) Nd7 
14. Bf4 ( { We should avoid } 14.Bb2 { here due to } 14...Ne5 { knocking off our light-squared bishop. } ) Nc5 
15. Bxd6 Qxd6 
16. Ne2 Bd7 ( { I wonder if Alsina Leal was considering the recapture with the pawn } 16...Nxd3 17.cxd3 { angling for a grip on the dark-squares. } ) 
17. Qf4 Qxf4 
18. Nxf4 { The ending is roughly equal, but I prefer White due to our slightly better pawn structure and some chances of getting a good knight vs bad bishop position. } Rfe8 
19. Bf1 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5c2]} 
20. Ne2 Ne6 ( 20...Bxc2? 21.Rec1 ) 
21. c3 c5 { Maybe this was not such a good idea! } ( 21...a5!? ) 
22. Rad1! {[%csl Rd5]} Red8 
23. Ng3 Bg6 
24. Re5! {[%cal Ge5d5]} { White has taken over the initiative. } d4 
25. cxd4 cxd4 
26. Bc4 { Black probably thought that the passed d-pawn was a strength, but in fact it can easily become a weakness. White's pieces are every active. } Rd6?! 
27. Ne4 Bxe4 
28. Rxe4 { Already threatening Bxe6 rounding up the pawn. } Rad8 
29. Re5! { The rook will swing over to a5, targeting the weak a7-pawn. Manoeuvres commence! } Kf8 
30. h4 g6 
31. g3 Kg7 
32. Kg2 Kf6 
33. Ra5 R8d7 
34. Rd2 h5 
35. Kf1 Nd8 
36. f4 Ne6 
37. Bxe6 { A committal decision, but White trusts that his active king will prevail. } fxe6 
38. Ke2 Rd5? ( { Black had to play } 38...Rc6! { keeping open the option of ...Rc3 when in need of counterplay. } ) 
39. Rxd5 Rxd5 
40. Kd3 {[%cal Gd2c2,Gc2c4,Gd2e2,Ge2e4]} { Having exchanged one pair of rooks, White will try to win the d-pawn. } Kf5 
41. Re2 Kg4 { Going for a forced variation. The engine feels like a draw will be the most likely result, but the lines are very complex. } 
42. Rxe6 Kxg3 
43. Rxg6+ Kxh4? ( 43...Kxf4 { was the correct move to maintain equality, but it feels like the h-pawn is the one to swap off in order to achieve a passed pawn. } ) 
44. Rg1! {[%csl Rh4]} { Now the king is cut off on the side of the board and the f-pawn will decide the game. } Kh3 
45. Rg5! Rd7 ( 45...Rxg5 46.fxg5 { winning. } ) 
46. f5 ( 46.Rxh5+ Kg4 47.Ra5 Kxf4 48.b4 { is also winning according to the engine. } ) h4 
47. f6 Kh2 
48. Rg7! Rd6 
49. f7 Rf6 
50. Kxd4 h3 
51. Ke5 Rf2 
52. Ke6 Re2+ 
53. Kd7 Rf2 
54. Ke7 Re2+ 
55. Kf8 Kh1 
56. Kg8 { A very nice endgame and, in general, a good game to understand some of the middlegame/endgame techniques in this line. } 1-0

