1. e4 c5 { My proposal against the Sicilian Defence is the so-called Closed System - a simple but effective way to face one of the most dangerous defences, that allows us to navigate the opening without having to memorize a long list of theoretical lines. } 
2. Nc3 { Before we develop our light-squared bishop by fianchetto, we need to control the d5-square to prevent our opponent from playing d7-d5. The knight development is by far the most popular move at all levels and, therefore, our main line. } e6 { Some players, especially those who play the Taimanov and/or Kan variations of the Sicilian, may decide to go for e6 with the idea ...d5 in the near future. This is a very reasonable approach, more suited towards those players who prefer not to play with a 'dragon' bishop. The key ideas against this system are to remember that:

a) A knight on d5 can be tactically very dangerous.

b) We put pressure on the centre and on the d5-pawn, and generally we castle on the kingside.

We shall play: } 
3. g3 { And now there are basically two paths that our opponent can choose from - either 3...d5 directly or after developing their knights. Let's check both options. } d5 
4. exd5 exd5 
5. Bg2 {[%cal Gc3d5]} { Black has to deal with the threat on the d-pawn. } d4 
6. Qe2+!? { A very annoying intermediate check. } Be7 { The best move, although at lower levels ...Qe7 (worse) is played a lot. } 
7. Nd5 Nc6 
8. d3 { With the idea Bf4 or Bg5. } Be6 
9. Nf4! {[%cal Gf4e6]} Bd7 { And now we can choose between forcing a draw by repetition, playing all-out for a win or a third, safer, path. } 
10. g4!? {[%mdl 32768]} { Interesting but quite risky. } Nf6 
11. g5 Ng4 
12. Nd5 Nge5 
13. Bf4 $13  {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4]} { With a very double-edged game ahead of us. We can play h4 and castle queenside and, at some point, swap off our opponent's bishop pair. } *

