1. e4 c5 { My proposal against the Sicilian Defence is the so-called Closed System - a simple but effective way to face one of the most dangerous defences, that allows us to navigate the opening without having to memorize a long list of theoretical lines. } 
2. Nc3 { Before we develop our light-squared bishop by fianchetto, we need to control the d5-square to prevent our opponent from playing d7-d5. The knight development is by far the most popular move at all levels and, therefore, our main line. } Nc6 
3. g3 {[%mdl 32768]} g6 { By far the most popular move at all levels (at master level, in more than 90% of the games, and nearly 50% at club level). } 
4. Bg2 Bg7 
5. d3 { The standard opening setup which can be arrived at by other move orders as well. We are planning Be3 followed by Qd2, challenging our opponent's dark-squared bishop. } e6 { Black plans to follow up with ...d6 and ...Nge7 with a harmonious setup. Many players also go 5...d6 here, but generally they will transpose on the next move with 6...e6. Every now and then we might encounter a player who opts for a dragon set-up, leaving the pawns on e7-d7 and developing the knight on f6. Our plan is set out in the model game between elite players Carlsen and Vallejo Pons of the 39th Olympiad [/variation/41248793/#/6/b]. } 
6. Be3! { This move is White's main idea. The bishop hits the c5-pawn, at the same time preparing Qd2 followed Bh6 whenever possible. } ( { There are other possible moves here such as } 6.f4 { or } ) ( 6.Nge2 { , leading to other opening setups, which can be used now and again to mix things up. Here are a couple of 'rules of thumb' to be taken into account, although they are definitely not set in stone.

1) Whenever possible, we should try to exchange the dark-squared bishops in order to weaken Black's kingside castled king.

2) Playing Nc3-d1 to challenge a black knight on d4 with c2-c3 is generally a good idea, specially if we don't have a knight on e2 or f3 to be traded. } ) d6 
7. Qd2! { One of the key ideas of our setup is to delay the pawn advance f2-f4 in order to play Bh6 as soon as Black develops his knight. If Black realises what we are trying to do, he may decide to postpone kingside development, in which case at some point we will be forced to play f4 followed by Nf3 and O-O. However, in my experience in this line, most of your typical opponents will just develop the knight. } Nge7 ( { The alternatives } 7...Nd4 { and } ) ( 7...Rb8 { , along with some other interesting options for Black such as the development of the knight on f6 instead of e7, are covered in the model games Adams-Ward [/variation/41248791/#/7/b] and Dworakowska-Madejska [/variation/41248790/#/7/b]. } ) 
8. Bh6! O-O 
9. h4! {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh6g7,Gg7h6,Gd2h6][%csl Yg7,Gh1]} { White's plan is extremely dangerous - to push the h-pawn to h5, trade bishops on g7 followed by pawns on g6 and then invade h6 with the queen for a mating attack. The model games Dworakowska-Madejska [/variation/41248790/#/7/b] and Adams-Ward [/variation/41248791/#/7/b] will help us understand how to implement this plan. } *

