6. Be3 e6 ( { Alternatively } 6...Nd4 7.Qd2 { will normally transpose to other lines, in which later on we shall play Nd1 and push back the knight. However, we have to be careful if Black plays } 7...Qa5 { and avoid } 8.Nd1?? { which drops a piece immediately after: } { Instead we can go 8.f4 e6 9.Nf3 Ne7 10.O-O O-O and now we have our own trick 11.Nd5! Nxf3+! 11...Qxd2?? 12.Nxe7+ Kh8 13.Bxd2 winning a piece. 12.Bxf3 Qd8 13.Nxe7+ Qxe7 14.c3 followed by d3-d4 with a pleasant position } 8...Nxc2+! ) ( { Another way of developing the black knight is via f6. In this case, we have to take into account a possible ...Ng4. } 6...Nf6 7.h3! { Preventing ...Ng4 } 7...O-O 8.Qd2 { As usual, our idea if to play Bh6 } 8...Nd4 { and here I suggest: (The following blunder has been seen at club level, and therefore we need to pay attention) } { 8...a6 9.Bh6 b5?? 10.Bxg7 Kxg7 11.e5! winning material. This type of tactic is one of the reasons they prefer to play ...Nge7 instead of ...Nf6. }{ Another interesting attacking plan can be played if they decide not to play their knight to d4, for example, 8...Rb8 9.f4 Bd7 10.Nf3 b5 11.O-O b4 12.Ne2 a5 and now 13.g4! a4 14.f5! with a flowing attack on the kingside. } 9.Nd1!? { with the standard attacking plan of c3-Bh6-Bxg7-f4-Nf3, for example. } { However, we must avoid at all costs dropping material with 9.Bh6? Bxh6 10.Qxh6 Nxc2+ and we are in deep trouble. } 9...e5 10.c3 Nc6 11.Ne2 Be6 { and now } 12.f4! Qd7 13.Nf2 b6 14.f5! gxf5 15.Bh6! { A very interesting idea to remember. White has a very dangerous attack in these positions if he gets in f4-f5 and is able to exchange the bishop on g7. } ) 
7. Qd2 Nge7 { Some players might decide to stick a knight on d4. } ( 7...Nd4 8.Nd1! { However, as a general rule, it's not a good idea to play Nd4 if White doesn't have a knight on e2 or f3. Now we can play c3 and push the knight back with tempi. } 8...Ne7 9.c3 Ndc6 10.Bh6! O-O 11.h4! { Our standard flank attack, which is fully explained in the main line. The d1 knight can be relocated via e3. } ) ( { Another reasonable alternative is } 7...Rb8 { but don't expect to see this much at beginner or intermediate levels. We can continue development with } 8.Nge2 Nd4 9.O-O b5 { and now } 10.Nc1!? { An interesting move that plans Nd1 followed by c3 without allowing Black to trade knights. } 10...Ne7 11.Nd1 b4 12.c3 bxc3 13.bxc3 Ndc6 14.Bh6 O-O 15.Bxg7 Kxg7 16.Ne3 { followed by the f4-f5 push. } ) 
8. Bh6 O-O 
9. h4 Bxh6!? { I would be surprised if your typical club opponent decided to exchange bishops on h6, as it looks very dangerous. However, it can be played, and we should know how to deal with it. } 
10. Qxh6 f6! { The key idea, preventing the advance of the h-pawn any further for the moment. } 
11. Qd2! { Our plan is clear-cut: h5-h6 placing a pawn wedge into our opponent's castled king and then trying to blast him open. } ( { We must avoid playing } 11.h5? g5! { followed by 12...Kh8 and 13...Ng8 trapping the queen. } ) e5 
