1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c6 { The solid Caro-Kann Defense, well known for being one of the most reliable choices for many of the world's best players, including Karpov himself! } 
2. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { We shall always occupy the center with both pawns if allowed. } d5 {[%cal Yd5e4][%csl Rb8,Gc8]} { Hitting the e4-pawn. Contrary to the French, the Caro-Kann doesn't shut in the light-squared bishop. However, the queenside knight will generally have to be developed to a more passive square. } 
3. Nd2! {[%cal Yc2c3][%csl Ge4]} { In order to deal with the threat on the e4-pawn, we have many options here. Nonetheless, most positional players enjoy the 'develop + control' option. The text is Karpov's preferred move - developing the knight, the e4-pawn is protected.

You might wonder why many players prefer to develop the knight to d2 instead of the seemingly more active square c3? The idea is to keep the option 'pawn to c3' available to bolster our centre if needed, specially if they decide to go for a fianchetto. } g6 {[%cal Gf8g7][%csl Rd4]} { This move is a combination of the Caro-Kann and the Modern Defense. It doesn't appear much at elite level, but quite a few club players enjoy the tricky nature of the line. The bishop on g7 will put pressure on the d4-pawn. } 
4. c3! {[%cal Yc3d4][%csl Gd4]} { One of the idea's behind 3. Nd2 - the c3-pawn can be used to bolster our center. } Bg7 
5. e5! {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3,Gf1d3,Ye1g1]} { We are already clearly better. We shall follow up with 6. f4 and 7. Ngf3, castle on the kingside and enjoy a lasting space advantage. } *

