1. e4 c6 { The solid Caro-Kann Defense, well known for being one of the most reliable choices for many of the world's best players, including Karpov himself! } 
2. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { We shall always occupy the center with both pawns if allowed. } d5 {[%cal Yd5e4][%csl Rb8,Gc8]} { Hitting the e4-pawn. Contrary to the French, the Caro-Kann doesn't shut in the light-squared bishop. However, the queenside knight will generally have to be developed to a more passive square. } 
3. Nd2! {[%cal Yc2c3][%csl Ge4]} { In order to deal with the threat on the e4-pawn, we have many options here. Nonetheless, most positional players enjoy the 'develop + control' option. The text is Karpov's preferred move - developing the knight, the e4-pawn is protected.

You might wonder why many players prefer to develop the knight to d2 instead of the seemingly more active square c3? The idea is to keep the option 'pawn to c3' available to bolster our centre if needed, specially if they decide to go for a fianchetto. } dxe4 ( { They don't have many more decent options, as the alternative } 3...Nf6 { runs into } 4.e5 { . } ) 
4. Nxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nd7 {[%cal Gg8f6]} { The Modern Variation, one of Karpov's own favourite pet lines with Black. In many books, the line is called the Karpov variation or even the Smyslov Variation. The idea is to develop the other knight to f6 and, after the trade, recapture without damaging their pawn structure. The former World Champion was also a specialist in the Caro-Kann Defence, playing with Black! } 
5. Nf3 Ngf6 
6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 
7. Ne5! {[%cal Gf1c4][%csl Rf7]} { Karpov played this move frequently. Although it does break one of the many opening rules ('don't move the same piece twice in the opening without good reason'), it hides a very dangerous idea. } Bf5?! { A dubious move, but one that many grand masters have played. Of course, at club level, it's the move you will most often see. } ( { Better is } 7...Be6 { followed by a kingside fianchetto, but that won't come easy to a traditional Caro-Kann player. In any case, after } 8.c3 { followed by 9. Bd3 and 10. O-O, we have a very pleasant opening position. } ) 
8. c3 {[%csl Gd4]} { A useful move that reinforces the center and anticipates their following move. } e6 ( { Alternatively, } 8...Nd7 { should be answered with } 9.Nxf7! Kxf7 10.Qf3! { and 11. g4, recovering the piece with a clear advantage. } ) 
9. g4! Bg6 
10. h4! {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 ( { The developing move } 10...Bd6 11.Qe2! { was played by Karpov against Zaitsev in 1970. The former World Champion opted to control the e4-square and protect the knight on e5 (in addition to preventing a queen swap). } { Notice that 11.h5 now would have been premature due to 11...Be4 , where 12.f3? is bad due to 12...Bxe5! and they come out on top. }) 
11. g5 Nd5 
12. Nxg6 fxg6 {[%csl Re6,Rg6,Rg7,Rh5]} 
13. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2g6][%csl Rg6]} { We are already much better, and Karpov just pounces on his opponent's king and his weakened pawn structure. And Karpov went on to win against Hort in the Bugojno MCL in 1978. The full game [/variation/41248784/#/13/w] has been analysed in the model game section of the course. } *

