1. e4 c6 { The solid Caro-Kann Defense, well known for being one of the most reliable choices for many of the world's best players, including Karpov himself! } 
2. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { We shall always occupy the center with both pawns if allowed. } d5 {[%cal Yd5e4][%csl Rb8,Gc8]} { Hitting the e4-pawn. Contrary to the French, the Caro-Kann doesn't shut in the light-squared bishop. However, the queenside knight will generally have to be developed to a more passive square. } 
3. Nd2! {[%cal Yc2c3][%csl Ge4]} { In order to deal with the threat on the e4-pawn, we have many options here. Nonetheless, most positional players enjoy the 'develop + control' option. The text is Karpov's preferred move - developing the knight, the e4-pawn is protected.

You might wonder why many players prefer to develop the knight to d2 instead of the seemingly more active square c3? The idea is to keep the option 'pawn to c3' available to bolster our centre if needed, specially if they decide to go for a fianchetto. } dxe4 ( { They don't have many more decent options, as the alternative } 3...Nf6 { runs into } 4.e5 { . } ) 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 {[%cal Yf6e4]} { This move used to be considered dubious at most but has lately come into fashion again, mainly due to the variation in which they recapture with the e-pawn. } 
5. Nxf6+ {[%mdl 32768]} { Trading knights and doubling a pawn is the only way to fight for the initiative. } exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6][%csl Yf6,Yf7,Yg7,Yh7]} { This move has come into fashion lately. They add an extra pawn to their castled king position and open up a nice diagonal for their bishop. Even so, we still have more space and an extra center pawn and, with precise play, we should leave the opening with a small advantage. } 
6. c3! {[%cal Gc3d4]} { Our standard center pawn movement, protecting d4 and opening up the d1-a4 diagonal. } Bd6 
7. Bd3 O-O 
8. Qc2! {[%csl Rh7]} { A key move to remember. We must force a weakness on the kingside if we want to claim an advantage. } Re8+ 
9. Ne2 h5!? { Taking advantage of the extra pawn wedged into their castled king, they defend the attack on their h-pawn with an aggressive advance. Both long castling and short castling are fine, but to be consistent with the first line, we will opt for the more aggressive option. } ( 9...g6?! { not the best defense as it leaves a hook on h5 for us to exploit, } 10.h4! Be6 11.h5 f5 12.Bd2 { followed by queenside castling and a kingside attack. Once again, although we have opened the game with our positional repertoire, every now, and again we will be forced to play with opposite side castled kings for the attack. However, when on the offensive, with our repertoire we shall always aim for clear attacking plans. } ) 
10. Be3 Nd7 
11. O-O-O Nf8 
12. c4! {[%cal Ge2c3]} { The key idea, allowing us to transfer the knight from e2 to c3. } Be6 
13. Nc3 {[%cal Gh2h3][%csl Gc4,Gd4]} { We do have an extra pawn in the center and can therefore claim a slight advantage, but they are solid. Trading off one of their bishops for our knight and, in general, playing for the endgame would be the correct strategy. } *

