1. e4 c6 { The solid Caro-Kann Defense, well known for being one of the most reliable choices for many of the world's best players, including Karpov himself! } 
2. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { We shall always occupy the center with both pawns if allowed. } d5 {[%cal Yd5e4][%csl Rb8,Gc8]} { Hitting the e4-pawn. Contrary to the French, the Caro-Kann doesn't shut in the light-squared bishop. However, the queenside knight will generally have to be developed to a more passive square. } 
3. Nd2! {[%cal Yc2c3][%csl Ge4]} { In order to deal with the threat on the e4-pawn, we have many options here. Nonetheless, most positional players enjoy the 'develop + control' option. The text is Karpov's preferred move - developing the knight, the e4-pawn is protected.

You might wonder why many players prefer to develop the knight to d2 instead of the seemingly more active square c3? The idea is to keep the option 'pawn to c3' available to bolster our centre if needed, specially if they decide to go for a fianchetto. } dxe4 ( { They don't have many more decent options, as the alternative } 3...Nf6 { runs into } 4.e5 { . } ) 
4. Nxe4 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5e4]} { Capablanca's pet move, and one of the most reliable in the Caro-Kann. They develop the bishop with tempo. } 
5. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5]} Bg6 
6. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} { Seemingly aggressive, this is actually a clean positional move. Before trading the light-squared bishops with Bd3, we gain some space on the kingside - this may be useful in some endings or as a prelude for a kingside attack. In this variation, the bishop trade is necessary; although hidden on h7, their light-squared bishop controls too many key squares. } h6 
7. h5 ( { Many players prefer the developing move } 7.Nf3 { first. After most of their most natural replies, the game will continue with 8. h5 transposing back to our main line. However, it's useful to notice that this move order might allow a quick Ne5-Qh5-Qf3 manoeuvre if they play noticeably bad - in other variations of the Caro-Kann, this tactical motive appears more frequently. } ) Bh7 
8. Nf3 e6 ( { The alternative } 8...Nd7 { pretty much transposes to our main line after } 9.Bd3 Bxd3 10.Qxd3 e6 { . } ) 
9. Bd3 { As mentioned before, this bishop trade is mandatory. } Bxd3 
10. Qxd3 Nd7 
11. Bd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { We finish our development and plan to castle on the queenside, where our king will be very safe. } ( { Many players prefer } 11.Bf4 { obviously a very decent move as well. However, they can then play } 11...Qa5+ 12.Bd2 { and now choose between } 12...Qc7 { transposing to one of our main lines. } { Also 12...Bb4 , is an interesting alternative. }) Ngf6 
12. O-O-O { The key position of the Capablanca variation. They can now choose between castling on the queenside or on the kingside. } Qc7 {[%cal Ge8c8]} { They go for queenside castling. } 
13. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3e5]} { A trademark Karpov move. We reposition the queen and prepare Ne5. In addition, good positional players use prophylaxis continuously - the queen on d3 will be uncomfortable under the x-ray attack of the d8-rook. } O-O-O 
14. Ne5! {[%cal Ye5f7]} { A good move, centralizing the knight and attacking the pawn on f7. } Nxe5 
15. dxe5 Nd5 
16. f4 {[%cal Gg3e4,Gc1b1,Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yc2c4][%csl Gg2]} { We shall follow up with Ne4 and Kb1 and then plan g4-g5 and/ or c4 with a big space advantage. } *

