1. e4 c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Nf6 
5. Nxf6+ gxf6 
6. c3 Bf5 
7. Nf3 Qc7 
8. g3 Nd7 
9. Bg2 O-O-O 
10. O-O e6 
11. Nh4! Bg6 
12. a4! { White initiates a strong queenside offensive. He plans to follow up with b4 and b5, taking advantage of the offensive power of the g2-bishop. } Bd6 
13. b4 f5 { Black tries to strike back with f5-f4, but it's too slow. } 
14. b5! c5 { Black does his best to keep the queenside closed. } 
15. a5! Qb8 { In order to play 16...a6 against 16. b6 but... } 
16. a6! b6 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2]} { Just look at the strength of White's light-squared bishop. } 
17. Bb7+ Kc7 
18. Qf3! {[%cal Gf3c6]} Rde8 
19. dxc5 bxc5 ( { Or } 19...Bxc5 20.Rd1 { and Black is busted. } ) 
20. b6+! { The black king can run, but it can't hide. } Kd8 ( { Alternatively } 20...Nxb6 21.Qc6+ Kd8 22.Bg5+ Be7 23.Rfd1+ Nd5 24.Rxd5+ exd5 25.Qxd5+ Qd6 26.Qxd6 { would have been a very nice combination to finish the game. } ) ( { Or } 20...axb6 21.Qc6+ Kd8 22.a7 { is also winning. } ) 
21. Rd1 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gf3c6]} Ke7 
22. bxa7 { And Black resigned. A powerful game by GM Javier Moreno Carnero. } ( { There are several ways to win, but the most simple is } 22.bxa7 Qxa7 23.Qc6 Qb8 24.a7 { and White promotes. } ) 1-0

