12. O-O-O Be7 
13. Qe2 O-O 
14. Nf1!? { A relatively new idea instead of the old Ne4, which generally helps them trade-off some pieces and reduce their space disadvantage. The main idea is to continue with g2-g4 followed by Ng3 and launch a direct attack on their king. } c5 
15. g4! { We generally don't worry too much about sacrificing a pawn on the g-file. In exchange, we will get wonderful attacking chances against our opponent's king. } cxd4 ( { If } 15...Nxg4 16.Rg1 { and now } 16...f5 { 16...Ngf6 loses to 17.Bxh6 . } 17.Qxe6+ { and Black's position is dreadful. } ) 
16. g5! hxg5 ( { Alternatively, I was surprised to see that } 16...Nd5 17.gxh6 Qb6 { this position is equal and, although Stockfish might be able to hold it, in practice things won't work out well for Black. White's attack is too powerful. } ) 
17. Bxg5 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5a2]} 
18. Kb1 Nb6 
19. h6! { White's attack flows smoothly. } Rfd8? { The decisive mistake. } ( { Although White is much better, Black had to play } 19...g6 { after which White recovers the pawn on d4 with a big advantage } 20.Rxd4 { . } ) 
20. Ne5! { Black resigned because he can't parry reasonably the threat of h7 followed by Nxf7 with a mating attack. } ( 20.Ne5 Rac8 21.h7+ Nxh7 { 21...Kh8 22.Nxf7 } 22.Qh5 { and checkmate is unavoidable. } ) 1-0

