1. e4 e6 { The French defence, one of Black's most solid and reliable options. } 
2. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} { We shall always try to occupy the center with both pawns if possible. } d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} { Their second move attacks our e-pawn. We can deal with the threat in many ways, but our repertoire suggests one of Karpov's favourite moves, the Tarrasch variation. } 
3. Nd2! {[%csl Ge4]} ( { By developing the knight, we protect our e-pawn and, more importantly, we avoid the Winawer variation, an unpleasant pin on b4, which might occur after } 3.Nc3 Bb4 { . } { Although our bishop on c1 is momentarily shut-in, the pros of our move outweigh the cons. They can now proceed in different ways - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...c5 and 3...Nf6 are the main options, but we shall also consider their main secondary moves. } ) Nf6 ( { After } 3...c5 { , the text is clearly the second most popular reply to the Tarrasch. Our e4-pawn is again under attack, and we must advance and attack their knight. } ) 
4. e5 Nfd7 
5. Bd3 {[%cal Yd3h7][%csl Gd3]} { In these d4-e5 pawn structures, our light-squared bishop usually lands on d3 to attack our opponent's castled king. } c5 
6. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4]} { We must reinforce our centre pawn chain. } Nc6 
7. Ne2 ( { Although } 7.Ngf3 { is also possible (going for the pawn sacrifice that is analysed in the 3...Be7 variation [/variation/41248697/#/3/b]), in this line I suggest the traditional development of the knight on e2 - the f3-square will then be available for the other knight. } ) cxd4 
8. cxd4 f6 {[%cal Gf6e5]} 
9. exf6 Nxf6 { Although the pawn on d4 is isolated from other connected pawns, it can't be considered weak in these positions. Not only can it support a minor piece on the e5 weak square, but it's not an "isolani" - the square in front is not vacant, and it also can't be attacked head-on. } 
10. O-O Bd6 
11. Nf3 {[%cal Gc1f4][%csl Ye5]} { We now plan to finish our development with Bf4, trading-off the dark-squared bishops in order to secure control over the important e5-outpost. } Qc7 
12. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5]} { Threatening 13. Nb5. } a6 
13. Bg5! { Developing our last minor piece, although we are not intending to exchange on f6! } O-O 
14. Bh4! {[%cal Gh4g3,Ga1c1,Gf1e1]} { The key position. Following Karpov's steps (he played this same line many times, with excellent results), we aim at exchanging the bishops while developing our rooks to the natural open and semi-open files. The model game between Karpov and Ostos [/variation/41248789/#/14/w] highlights some more ideas in the variation. } *

