1. e4 e6 { The French defence, one of Black's most solid and reliable options. } 
2. d4 { We shall always try to occupy the center with both pawns if possible. } d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} { Their second move attacks our e-pawn. We can deal with the threat in many ways, but our repertoire suggests one of Karpov's favourite moves, the Tarrasch variation. } 
3. Nd2! {[%csl Ge4]} ( { By developing the knight, we protect our e-pawn and, more importantly, we avoid the Winawer variation, an unpleasant pin on b4, which might occur after } 3.Nc3 Bb4 { . } { Although our bishop on c1 is momentarily shut-in, the pros of our move outweigh the cons. They can now proceed in different ways - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...c5 and 3...Nf6 are the main options, but we shall also consider their main secondary moves. } ) dxe4 
4. Nxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} { With their move, they release the tension in the center. Although the line is considered to be solid enough, we do have an extra pawn in the center and better development - therefore, nothing to worry about. } Bd7 { The so-called Fort Knox Variation. } 
5. Nf3 Bc6 {[%cal Ge4g5][%csl Ye4]} { An interesting way to develop their light-squared bishop. Many options are available to us - for example, 6. Neg5 is quite interesting - but in the spirit of our repertoire we shall stick to solid development and center play. } 
6. Bd3 Nd7 
7. O-O Ngf6 
8. Ng3! {[%csl Gd4,Ye6]} { Avoiding trades, as we do have a space advantage. } Be7 
9. Re1 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gc1f4,Gd1e2]} { With the follow-up ideas of c3-and Bf4 if they exchange their bishop for our knight on f3, the main idea of the line. One of our reference games in this line is Karpov-Stojanovic [/variation/41248786/#/9/w], in which they preferred to go ...b6 and ...Bb7. } *

