1. e4 e6 { The French defence, one of Black's most solid and reliable options. } 
2. d4 { We shall always try to occupy the center with both pawns if possible. } d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} { Their second move attacks our e-pawn. We can deal with the threat in many ways, but our repertoire suggests one of Karpov's favourite moves, the Tarrasch variation. } 
3. Nd2! {[%csl Ge4]} ( { By developing the knight, we protect our e-pawn and, more importantly, we avoid the Winawer variation, an unpleasant pin on b4, which might occur after } 3.Nc3 Bb4 { . } { Although our bishop on c1 is momentarily shut-in, the pros of our move outweigh the cons. They can now proceed in different ways - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...c5 and 3...Nf6 are the main options, but we shall also consider their main secondary moves. } ) dxe4 
4. Nxe4 { With their move, they release the tension in the center. Although the line is considered to be solid enough, we do have an extra pawn in the center and better development - therefore, nothing to worry about. } Nd7 { The Rubinstein variation. Their idea is to develop the other knight on f6 and trade-off some pieces. We shall continue to develop. } 
5. Nf3 Ngf6 
6. Nxf6+ {[%mdl 32768]} Nxf6 ( { Considerably worse is } 6...Qxf6 { as after } 7.Bg5! { their queen is in big danger! } 7...Qg6 8.Bd3 Qh5 9.h3! { . } ) 
