1. e4 e6 { The French defence, one of Black's most solid and reliable options. } 
2. d4 { We shall always try to occupy the center with both pawns if possible. } d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} { Their second move attacks our e-pawn. We can deal with the threat in many ways, but our repertoire suggests one of Karpov's favourite moves, the Tarrasch variation. } 
3. Nd2! {[%csl Ge4]} ( { By developing the knight, we protect our e-pawn and, more importantly, we avoid the Winawer variation, an unpleasant pin on b4, which might occur after } 3.Nc3 Bb4 { . } { Although our bishop on c1 is momentarily shut-in, the pros of our move outweigh the cons. They can now proceed in different ways - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...c5 and 3...Nf6 are the main options, but we shall also consider their main secondary moves. } ) Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} { The Guimard variation. A strange-looking move for the French, as ...c5 is no longer possible. However, if one isn't well-prepared, it can come as a shock: the d-pawn is under attack and our queen is no longer protecting it. } 
4. Ngf3 {[%mdl 32768]} { The best move, developing and protecting the pawn. } ( { The alternative } 4.c3 { has always been considered slightly worse due to } 4...e5! ) Nf6 
5. e5 Nd7 
