7. O-O! ( { Note that } 7.Ne4 { hitting the queen is premature due to } 7...Qb4+ { . } ) Nf6 
8. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3d4]} { Just in time to get our pawn back. } Nc6 ( { If they are stubborn, we might score a quick win! } 8...e5? 9.Re1! Nc6 10.Bf4! { and once again they are in deep trouble - the pin on the e-file is deadly. } ) 
9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 
10. Nxd4 ( { Endgame specialists occasionally go for } 10.Qxd4 Qxd4 11.Nxd4 { but, in general, we prefer to play with both queens on the board. } ) a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} { A key position - there are many decent options here, but a lot of theory has to be memorized. Karpov came up with a simple solution which I think is quite OK for practical play at our level. } 
11. a4! {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gd4f3,Yd1e2]} { Preventing one of their ideas, namely ...b5 and ...Bb7. We will follow up with 12. b3, 13. Bb2 and 14. Nf3 against most of their moves, with an attack on the kingside. } *

