1. e4 e6 { The French defence, one of Black's most solid and reliable options. } 
2. d4 { We shall always try to occupy the center with both pawns if possible. } d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} { Their second move attacks our e-pawn. We can deal with the threat in many ways, but our repertoire suggests one of Karpov's favourite moves, the Tarrasch variation. } 
3. Nd2! {[%csl Ge4]} ( { By developing the knight, we protect our e-pawn and, more importantly, we avoid the Winawer variation, an unpleasant pin on b4, which might occur after } 3.Nc3 Bb4 { . } { Although our bishop on c1 is momentarily shut-in, the pros of our move outweigh the cons. They can now proceed in different ways - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPPN1PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...c5 and 3...Nf6 are the main options, but we shall also consider their main secondary moves. } ) c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} { This is their main option. Our knight on d2 blocks our queen from protecting d4, so it makes sense for them to strike in the center. } 
4. exd5 exd5 { Although the French is better known for closed pawn structures, every now, and again we shall come upon an open structure, in this case an isolated pawn. } 
5. Ngf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nc6 ( { The line } 5...c4 { is possible but after } 6.b3! { we immediately put our opponent's pawn chain under pressure. } ) 
6. Bb5! {[%csl Rc6]} { Developing the bishop actively and pinning the knight in our fight for the center squares. } a6 { The alternative is simply weak. Black can't spend so much time with pawn moves. } 
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 
8. O-O! {[%cal Gf1e1]} Bd6 
9. dxc5! Bxc5 
10. Nb3! {[%cal Gb3c5]} Bd6 
11. Qd4! {[%cal Gd4g7]} { Each of our moves comes with tempo by attacking one of their weaknesses. We are clearly better here and will soon trade off our opponent's dark-squared bishop. } Nf6 
12. Re1+ {[%csl Re8]} Be6 
13. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6,Rf4]} O-O 
14. Bxd6 Qxd6 
15. Qc5! Qxc5 
16. Nxc5 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc2c3][%csl Gc5,Re6]} { With a very good endgame. We enjoy nice outposts for our knights on d4 and c5, and our opponent's light-squared bishop is very passive - the pawns on c6 and d5 render it totally ineffective. } *

