1. e4 e6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 dxe4 
4. Nxe4 Bd7 
5. Nf3 Bc6 
6. Bd3 Nd7 
7. O-O Ngf6 
8. Ng3! Be7 
9. Re1 O-O 
10. Qe2 b6?! { A dubious idea by GM Stojanovic. Of course, if White allows his opponent to drop back his bishop to b7 and then play ...c5, he will be perfectly fine. However, Karpov spots the idea and quickly nips it in the bud. } ( { The main line of the Fort Knox runs } 10...Bxf3 11.Qxf3 c6 12.c3 { and the general consensus is that White has a small but enduring advantage thanks to the bishop pair. It must be said, however, that Black's position is quite robust and not at all easy to break down. } ) 
11. Ba6! Rb8 
12. c4 Bb7 
13. Bxb7 Rxb7 
14. Ne5! Qc8? ( { Black should have played } 14...Nxe5 15.dxe5 Nd7 16.b3 { is clearly very nice for White, but it's still a game. } ) 
15. Nc6! {[%cal Gc6e7]} { A fantastic idea. The knight on c6 dominates the fianchettoed rook. Black must try to escape by means of an exchange with ...Nb8. } Re8 
16. Bg5! Bf8 ( { Black can't play yet } 16...Nb8 17.Nxe7+ Rxe7 18.Bxf6 gxf6 19.Qg4+ Kh8 20.Nh5 { and White's attack crashes through. } ) 
17. Bxf6 Nxf6 
18. Nh5! {[%csl Gc6,Rf8]} { Beautiful positional chess. Karpov is angling for a knight vs bishop unbalance. } Nd7 
19. Qg4 Kh8 ( 19...Nb8? 20.Nf6+ ) 
20. Re3! {[%cal Ge3h3]} Nb8 { The knight is finally challenged, but it's too late: White's attack is too dangerous. } 
21. Rg3?! { Attacking g7 but allowing his opponent a chance to defend. This is Karpov's only inaccuracy in the game. } ( { Probably better was } 21.Ne5! c5 22.Rh3 { playing for the attack. } ) f5? { Black returns the mistake. } ( { The only move was } 21...e5! { threatening to exchange queens } 22.Qxc8 Rxc8 23.Nxe5 c6 { and of course White has a healthy extra pawn, but there is still a long game ahead. } ) ( { Or } 21...Nxc6 22.Nxg7 22...Rd8 23.Nf5 { and it's game over. } ) 
22. Qh4! Nxc6 
23. Nf6! {[%cal Gh4h7]} h6 { And now a wonderful mating pattern. } ( 23...gxf6 24.Qxf6+ Bg7 25.Qxg7 ) 
24. Qxh6+!! gxh6 
25. Rg8 1-0

