7. Ne2 cxd4 
8. cxd4 f6 
9. exf6 Nxf6 { Although the pawn on d4 is isolated from other connected pawns, it can't be considered weak in these positions. Not only can it support a minor piece on the e5 weak square, but it's not an "isolani" - the square in front is not vacant, and it also can't be attacked head-on. } 
10. Nf3 Bd6 
11. O-O Qc7 
12. Nc3 a6 
13. Bg5 O-O 
14. Bh4! {[%cal Gh4g3]} { The key position. We aim at exchanging the dark-squared bishops while developing our rooks to the natural open and semi-open files. The exchange of bishops will enhance our control over the dark squares. } Bd7 
15. Re1 Rae8 
16. Rc1 Qb8 
17. Bb1! {[%cal Gd1d3]} { After placing his rooks on the open and semi-open files, Karpov prepares the classical bishop and queen battery. } Kh8 
18. a3 Bf4 {[%cal Gf4c1]} 
19. Rc2 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4h2]} 
20. h3 Nh6 
21. Bg5! { Finally forcing the exchange of bishops. } Nf5 
22. Bxf4 Qxf4 
23. Ne2 Qd6 
24. Rd2 { Probably already in this position, Karpov is thinking of how to exchange two pairs of minor pieces and end up with a strong knight on e5 (or d4) against Black's light-squared passive bishop. } Rf6 
25. Nc3 Ref8 
26. Ne5! {[%csl Ge5]} Be8 ( 26...Nxe5? 27.dxe5 { wins on the spot. } ) 
27. Nxc6! Bxc6 
28. Qe2! {[%csl Ge5]} { Note how Karpov always keeps e5 under control. } Qf4 
29. Bxf5! { The exchange of a good bishop is always difficult. One piece of advice - the exchanged pieces fall back into the box, therefore you need to keep in mind the unbalance of the pieces that stay on the board'. } Rxf5 
30. Qe3 {[%csl Gc3,Rc6]} Qh4 
31. Qg3! { Karpov wants to force an ending where he can calmly impose his positional advantage. } Qf6 
32. Nd1! { Initiating the re-routing of the knight towards e5. Fantastic stuff! } Rf4 
33. Re5! h6 
34. Ne3 Bd7 
35. Ng4 Qd8 
36. Re3 Qa5 
37. Rc3 Be8 
38. Ne5 { And White has achieved his game. Karpov makes it seem effortless. } Bh5 
39. Nd7! { The rook on f8 is overloaded - it has to protect the back-rank but also his colleague on f4. } R8f5 
40. Rc8+ Kh7 
41. b4 Qb5 
42. Rc7 { Taking control of the seventh rank, with the direct threat Nf6+. The game is over. } Rf7 
43. Nf8+! Kg8 ( 43...Rxf8 44.Qxg7 ) 
44. Nxe6 Qe8 
45. Nxg7! Qe1+ 
46. Kh2 1-0

