1. e4 d6 { The Pirc Defence. They allow us to construct a two-pawn center with the idea of attacking it from afar by means of a kingside fianchetto and, generally, the pawn thrust e7-e5. } 
2. d4 { By now, it's clear that we should always occupy the center with two pawns if possible. } Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 
3. Nc3 { Protecting our e-pawn and developing towards the center. } g6 
4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Yc1e3,Yg1e2,Yh2h3]} { The fianchetto variation. } ( { During his career, Karpov was usually more inclined to go for the classic } 4.Nf3 { + 5. Be2 setup, also a good alternative. However, he would occasionally try out the fianchetto and, more importantly, the middlegame ideas are similar to our repertoire proposal against the Sicilian. } ) Bg7 
5. Bg2 {[%csl Ye4]} O-O 
6. Nge2 {[%cal Ra7a6,Rb7b5,Ge1g1,Gc1e3,Yf2f4,Yg3g4][%csl Gg2]} { This line is regularly played in master games but hardly every seen at the lower levels, meaning that we shall also bring a surprise element to the table.

By developing our bishop to g2, we already prevent any ...a6, ...b5 ideas that they may have entertained for the game. Our plan is quite simple: we shall generally castle kingside, play h3 and Be3 to finish our development, and then commence a kingside assault on our opponent's king with f4 and, sometimes, g4 and Ng3. } e5 {[%cal Ge5d4]} ( { They will nearly always go for this typical move, sometimes preluded by } 6...Nc6 { or } ) ( 6...Nbd7 { . Our plan is basically the same in both cases. } ) 
7. O-O { Although playable, I do not recommend this move. } Nc6 {[%cal Ge5d4]} 
8. h3 {[%cal Yf6g4]} ( 8.Be3? Ng4 { is very good for them. } ) exd4 
9. Nxd4 Nxd4 
10. Qxd4 Re8 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Rd4,Gg7]} { With the threat 11...Nxe4 is a line we shall try to avoid in this repertoire. } 
*

